{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631364"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17365"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10055"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75067"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10055"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60574"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7840"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23544"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23550"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75067"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team conducts an observational study examining the relationship between exercise and academic performance in university students. They find that students who exercise more frequently achieve higher grades.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a likely confounding variable in this study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Time of day exercise occurs","Type of exercise performed","Socioeconomic status","Location of exercise facility","Duration of exercise sessions"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESocioeconomic status\u003C/strong\u003E is likely confounding the relationship between exercise and academic performance because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStudents from higher socioeconomic backgrounds often have better access to exercise facilities and time for physical activity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESocioeconomic status independently influences academic performance through various mechanisms including access to resources and educational support\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt affects both the exposure (exercise) and outcome (academic performance)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options all relate only to the exposure and would not create confounding because they do not independently influence both exercise habits and academic performance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis example demonstrates how confounding variables can create apparent associations between variables that may not be directly causally related. Controlling for socioeconomic status through study design or analysis would help reveal the true relationship between exercise and academic performance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Confounding happens when a third variable influences both the exposure and outcome, creating a false association.","Confounding bias can be controlled through study design (randomisation, matching) or statistical analysis (stratification, regression).","Age, sex, and socioeconomic status are common confounding variables in epidemiological studies."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationship